      <hedline>
        <hl1>Gluten-Free Food</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Claire Lazebnik scores Jan 3 article for lumping phrase 'gluten-free' with other packaging terminology; says it is vital for people to know what foods can be safely eaten by people with celiac disease and other ailments (Jan 3 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your article included the phrase ''gluten free'' as if it, too, was one of those meaningless phrases meant to make people believe they're buying a healthier, more ''natural'' product. I have a son with celiac disease, which is an auto-immune disease that causes the intestines to destroy themselves if gluten is ingested. Seeing the words ''gluten free'' on packaging thrills me: it means I can safely buy it and serve it to my son without having to read all the ingredients and check with the manufacturer.</p>
        <p>Claire LaZebnik  Pacific Palisades, Calif.</p>
      </block>
